node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Recovery and Resilience
.
Everyone is susceptible to invisible wounds. Being able to recognize one of these wounds, and using positive language when discussing it, supports a positive culture across the Department of the Air Force and could save a life. It is important for Airmen and Guardians to seek help for invisible wounds, taking that first step towards recovery.
.
This video describes the importance of Airmen and Guardians seeking help for invisible wounds and how taking that first step towards recovery results in positive outcomes and enhanced resilience.
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Risk, Impact, and Available Resources
.
Over the past five years, United States Department of the Air Force’s Invisible Wounds Initiative has implemented solutions that drive timely, proactive case handling, equitable, informed interactions and decisions, engaged leadership and a supportive environment, and accessible, effective care delivery. 
.
Everyone is susceptible to invisible wounds. The impact of invisible wounds and can develop at any time, in any place, in or out of uniform.
.
Learn more at: https://go.usa.gov/xszpN
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Invisible Wounds: Signs and Symptoms
.
Since its inception in 2016, the United States Department of the Air Force’s Invisible Wounds Initiative has been a leader in creating a supportive culture for #Airmen living with invisible wounds. Being able to recognize an invisible wound could save a life. Airman can learn to see the signs and symptoms of invisible wounds in others that they may see in themselves.
.
#InvisibleWounds #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth

node.text:
Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Charles Q. Brown, Jr., & @cmsaf_official discuss how empowering Airmen will lead to success in building the future Air Force today. They also discussed Accelerate Change or Lose, the Action Orders, leadership and followership, how to rise above bias & self-limitations, and the future of the #AirForce.
.
The primary focus of this call was to connect with Airmen across the world, and give insight to how the Action orders, new Air Force missions statement and developmental guidance are being implemented for the Total Force.
.
#RealTalk #CoffeeTalk #Future #Empowerment #Questions

node.text: Flying, fighting and winning since 1947. #USAF73

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by U.S. Air Force on September 18, 2021. May be an image of aircraft, outdoors and text that says '74 YEARS OF FLY, ( & WIN FIGHT 1947-2021 74 U,S AIRF FORCE ANNIVERSARY'.

node.text:
Today is the #AirForce's 74th Birthday!
.
From humble beginnings in 1947, we stand on the shoulders of great Airmen who have helped build the world's greatest Air Force. We thank each and every person who has helped to build credibility and trust for our nation and our allies.
.
#happybirthday #celebration #yearsold #year #USAF74

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by U.S. Air Force on September 18, 2021. May be an image of 3 people and people standing.

node.text:
USAF tradition calls for the most junior ranking Airman and most senior ranking Airman present to cut the birthday cake! 

Here Department of the Air Force senior leaders slice the cake at the Pentagon during a ceremony celebrating #USAF74!

📷 by Eric Dietrich

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by U.S. Air Force on September 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing, military uniform and sky.

node.text:
Honoring with Dignity and Aloha

Member's of the Hawaii @airnationalguard’s Honor Guard display various ceremonial military honors during sunrise at Foster's Point, Joint Base Pearl Harbor-Hickam, Hawaii. The mission of the HIANG Honor Guard is to represent the Airmen of the Hawaii Air National Guard to the public and the world while performing a variety of ceremonies with dignity and aloha. 
.
#honorguard #flag #sunrise
.
📸  by MSgt Mysti Bicoy

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by U.S. Air Force on September 17, 2021. May be an image of text.

node.text:
Today is POW/MIA Recognition Day. We recognize the more than half-million service members who have, at one time, been held as prisoners of war.
.
Nearly 82,000 members remain unaccounted for; still, they are #NeverForgotten. The U.S. Department of Defense, as a whole, is committed to bringing every member home.
.
#POW #MIA

node.text:
Learning the "Why"
.
Secretary of the Air Force Frank Kendall directed the COVID-19 vaccine implementation guidelines for Department of the Air Force military members recently.
.
We showcase Master Sgt. Victoria Yale. Learn why she was vaccinated, and the responsibility she believes all Airmen have to get vaccinated.
.
#COVID #COVIDvaccine #COVID19

node.text:
Airman 1st Class Alyssa Oxley and Airman 1st Class Booke Kotwica, 15th Airlift Squadron loadmasters, prepare a C-17 Globemaster III for take-off at @teamcharleston, South Carolina. The C-17 is capable of rapid strategic delivery of troops and all types of cargo to main operating bases or directly to forward bases in the deployment areas. 
.
#aircraft #militaryphotography #c17 #cargo
.
 📸 by TSgt Michael Cossaboom

node.text:
Airmen from the 155th Chemical Biological Radiological Nuclear Enhanced Response Force Package search and extraction team discuss the status of patients found within a building collapse during a CERFP patient rescue and treatment exercise in Lincoln, Neb.
. 
The CERFP mission is to assist local incident commanders with the nationalguard as the first military responders in either a state or a federal role. 
.
@airnationalguard | #firstresponder #training #exercise 
.
📸  by A1C Alexander D. Schriner

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by U.S. Air Force on September 14, 2021. May be an image of 4 people, people standing and outdoors.

node.text:
The last of the Doolittle Raiders
.
Lt. Col. Richard “Dick” Cole, the last of the Doolittle Raiders, was honored and posthumously promoted to the rank of colonel recently at the Joint Base San Antonio-Fort Sam Houston.
.
Cole was the last surviving member of the Doolittle Raiders, a group of 80 crew members led by Lt. Col. James “Jimmy” Doolittle, who flew 16 B-25 Mitchell bombers from the USS Hornet April 18, 1942, en route to an air raid to attack Tokyo in World War II, after the Japanese had bombed Pearl Harbor Dec. 7, 1941.
.
#airpower #bomber #doolittleraid
.
📸 by Tristin English

#AirForce optometry teams across the globe apply extensive knowledge of unique operating environments to prescribe precision optical devices designed to enhance performance, survivability and lethality of Airmen. 
.
Approximately 142 optometrists and 236 ophthalmic technicians provide care for 2.6 million active duty, dependent and retiree beneficiaries around the force.
.
@teamtyndall #glasses #eye #optometry #sight
.
📹 by SrA Jacob Dastas

Maj. Michael Brewer, @afthunderbirds flight demonstration team pilot, flies over the Cleveland Browns stadium during a show in Cleveland, Ohio.

The Thunderbirds squadron is an @aircombatcommand unit composed of eight pilots, four support officers, three civilians and over 130 enlisted personnel performing in 28 career fields. They are tasked with representing the finest qualities of the #AirForce at home and abroad. 
.
#militaryaviation #thunderbirds #flyover #aircraft #f16
.
